My Visual Data Story

STATS220 Project 4

Alistair Wong

Climbing Sessions

In total I logged 12 climbing sessions, 4 during Project 2 and 8 during the duration of this project. The form that was used recorded the date and time of each log, from this the day of the week was extracted and attempts were sorted by day of week as seen below in the plot. Looking at the plot it seems that I climb the most on Tuesday and the least on Wednesdays. Tuesday has 60 attempts and Wednesday having 18 attempts, about one third the attempts of Tuesday. This Plot is interesting to see as Wednesday is the day that I work and after work there is not a lot of time after to climb so that it makes sense that, that is when I have the least attempts.

Attempts by Grade

For the following plots only the most recent sessions were used as these contained data about the style of climbing and wall type that was not previously included

There were 163 total attempts over 7 sessions averaging 23 attempts per session and 9 climbs per session (rounded down). Below is a plot of attempts by each grade from 1 to 8. Since this plot was quite spread out I decided to separate this into two different plots, the first one ranging from V1-4 and the second covering V5-8.

Attempts by Grade V1 to V4

Each climb in V1 and V2 had only 1 attempt except for 1 at V2, this is because I topped the climb on the first try and so there were no further attempts.

V3 has an average of 2.44 attempts with the most attempts I tried being 7.

V4 has an average of 2.4 attempts with the most attempts at 6. This was a dynamic slab problem which required accuracy and trial and error, so the 6 attempts make sense.

Overall from V1-4 the average attempts I made was 1.824. This makes me believe that my level of climbing is above at least V4 as at all styles and types of wall I was able to top the climb within 2 attempts.

Attempts by Grade V5 to V8

At V5 the average attempts I took per climb was 2.083 and at V6 the average attempts were slightly increased at 2.25 attempts. However there were two instances at v6 were I was not able to top the climb, still this indicates the same as V1-4 that I am able to climb comfortably at levels between V1-6.

At V7 the average attempts was at 7.125 and V8 has 6.4 a decrease, however it is important to note there were both less climbs and less successful climbs. This can be confirmed with what I observe where I often give up on a V8 after a couple attempts. At V7 3 out of the 8 climbs I tried I managed to climbed. V7 and V8 are skewed and more data needs to be collected to be able to get a better understanding on how many attempts it would take. It also is not a fair evaluation on how many attempts it takes to top a V7 or 8 as many more sessions are not accounted for and after topping a climb repeating it is a lot easier.

At V7 this is my projecting level, where I have to project a climb over multiple sessions and at V8 this is also similar where I only completed 1 out of the 6 I attempted. This can be seen as my current cap.

Grade Success

Looking at the plot V1 V2, V4, and V5 have 100% success rate which is expected as these are the lower levels. V3 has a slightly lower success rate at around ~85%, this is only due to one climb where I gave up after 1 attempt. At V6 this starts to lower down to 80% this becomes the limit on where I am able to flash a boulder, or get it first try. At V7 the chance that I top a boulder decreases to about 37% and at V8 this goes down to about 20%.

This shows me the current level I am at, which is about a V6-7 Climber. ## Success by Wall

From the plot the I was most successful on the Overhang wall followed by Slab, Overhang + Slab then Cave. Cave I expected to be the lowest as this is my least favourite type of wall. However what was surprising was that the most successful type of wall was overhang and not slab or the combination of the two. It seems that I am better at overhang climbs than I thought and as expected not very good at cave climbing.

Success by Style

From the plot I was most successful on powerful and dynamic climbs followed by slopey then crack. Crack is harder to judge since there were only two climbs that I attempted and only managed to top 1, which was at a lower level. Slopey holds have been one of my weaknesses and so that is something to work on.

Conclusion

This project has helped me to identify my weaknesses which are climbs that are set in the cave and climbs that are slopey.
